SIMPLE: fog
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fog
<hw>Fog</hw> <pr>(f⟦ocr⟧g)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Scot.
<ets>fog</ets>, <ets>fouge</ets>, moss, <ets>foggage</ets> rank grass,
LL. <ets>fogagium</ets>, W. <ets>ffwg</ets> dry grass.]</ety>
<fld>(Agric.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A second growth of grass;
aftergrass.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Dead or decaying grass remaining on
land through the winter; -- called also
<altname>foggage</altname>.</def> <mark>[Prov.Eng.]</mark>
<au>Halliwell.</au> <note>Sometimes called, in New England, <altname>old
tore</altname>. In Scotland, <xex>fog</xex> is a general name for
moss.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fog</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fog
<hw>Fog</hw> <pr>(f⟦ocr⟧g)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <fld>(Agric.)</fld>
<def>To pasture cattle on the fog, or aftergrass, of; to eat off the fog
from.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fog</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fog
<hw>Fog</hw> <pr>(f⟦ocr⟧g)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Etymol.
uncertain.]</ety> <def>To practice in a small or mean way; to
pettifog.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where wouldst thou fog to get a fee?</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fog</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fog
<hw>Fog</hw> <pr>(f⟦ocr⟧g)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Dan.
snee<ets>fog</ets> snow falling thick, drift of snow, driving snow, cf.
Icel. <ets>fok</ets> spray, snowdrift, <ets>fj⟦umac⟧k</ets> snowstorm,
<ets>fj⟦umac⟧ka</ets> to drift.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Watery vapor
condensed in the lower part of the atmosphere and disturbing its
transparency. It differs from cloud only in being near the ground, and
from mist in not approaching so nearly to fine rain. See
<er>Cloud</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A state of mental confusion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>Cloudiness or partial opacity
of those parts of a developed film or a photograph which should be
clear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Fog alarm</b></col>, <col><b>Fog bell</b></col>,
<col><b>Fog horn</b></col>, etc.</mcol>, <cd>a bell, horn, whistle or
other contrivance that sounds an alarm, often automatically, near places
of danger where visible signals would be hidden in thick weather.</cd>
-- <col><b>Fog bank</b></col>, <cd>a mass of fog resting upon the sea,
and resembling distant land.</cd> -- <col><b>Fog ring</b></col>, <cd>a
bank of fog arranged in a circular form, -- often seen on the coast of
Newfoundland.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fog</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Fog
<hw>Fog</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Fogged</conjf> <pr>(#)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fogging</conjf> <pr>(#)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
envelop, as with fog; to befog; to overcast; to darken; to
obscure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>To render semiopaque or cloudy,
as a negative film, by exposure to stray light, too long an exposure to
the developer, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fog</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Fog
<hw>Fog</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>To
show indistinctly or become indistinct, as the picture on a negative
sometimes does in the process of development.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fog belt</ent>⟦br⟧
